<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="382" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1269,2014]" pageId="4" pageNumber="382">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,1269,1294]" pageId="4" pageNumber="382">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
(after 
<bibRefCitation author="Delgado-Blas" box="[350,724,1269,1294]" pageId="4" pageNumber="382" refString="Delgado-Blas, V. H. &amp; Diaz-Diaz, O. (2013) Malacoceros longiseta, a new species of Spionidae (Annelida: Polychaeta) from Venezuela. Marine Biodiversity, 43, 181 - 187. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1007 / s 12526 - 013 - 0144 - 9" type="journal article" year="2013">
Delgado-Blas &amp; Díaz-Díaz 
<number box="[665,724,1270,1294]" pageId="4" pageNumber="382" value="2013.0">2013</number>
</bibRefCitation>
, amended). Prostomium broad anteriorly, T-shaped, triangularshaped, bell-shaped; broadly rounded along anterior margin; occipital antenna absent. Eyes present, irregularly arranged or arranged in pairs, or eyes absent. Caruncle entire, trilobed or buttonlike. Nuchal organs as two small ciliated grooves posteriolaterally to the caruncle. Palps ventrally grooved. Peristomium reduced to moderately developed. Eversible, sac-like proboscis. Cirriform branchiae from chaetiger 
<number box="[1055,1069,1414,1438]" pageId="4" pageNumber="382" value="1.0">1</number>
to end or nearly end of body; basally fused or free to notopodial lamellae; branchiae usually overlapping at dorsal midline in anterior segments, reduced in length and thickness in middle and posterior segments. Dorsal ciliated organs present or absent. Transverse ciliated bands across the dorsum present. Parapodia 
<number box="[922,964,1522,1546]" pageId="4" pageNumber="382" value="2.0" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="1.0">
1– 
<date box="[950,964,1522,1546]" pageId="4" pageNumber="382">3</date>
</number>
may be shifted dorsally to subsequent segments. Chaetae include simple capillaries, scalpel chaetae, neuropodial uni-, bi-, tri- or quadridentate hooded hooks. Sabre chaetae present. Pygidium with 2, 4, 6, 6– 
<number box="[772,785,1593,1618]" pageId="4" pageNumber="382" value="8.0">8</number>
, or 
<number box="[825,896,1593,1618]" pageId="4" pageNumber="382" value="22.5" valueMax="30.0" valueMin="15.0">15–30</number>
anal cirri or with two anal cirri and a rounded or spatuliform dorsal lobe. Eggs with complex thick egg membranes ornamented resembling honeycombs with numerous cortical alveoli (
<bibRefCitation author="Blake" box="[453,730,1665,1690]" pageId="4" pageNumber="382" refString="Blake, J. A. &amp; Arnofsky, P. L. (1999) Reproduction and larval development of the spioniform Polychaeta with application to systematics and phylogeny. Hydrobiologia, 402, 57 - 106. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1007 / 978 - 94 - 017 - 2887 - 4 _ 4" type="journal article" year="1999">
Blake &amp; Arnofsky 
<number box="[670,730,1666,1690]" pageId="4" pageNumber="382" value="1999.0">1999</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). Male gametes are ect-aquasperm 
<typeStatus box="[1128,1176,1666,1690]" pageId="4" pageNumber="382">type</typeStatus>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Guerin" pageId="4" pageNumber="382" refString="Guerin, J. P. &amp; Kerambrun, P. (1984) Role of reproductive characters in the taxonomy of spionids and elements of speciation in the Malacoceros fuliginosus complex. Fortschritte der Zoologie, 29, 317 - 333." type="journal article" year="1984">
Guérin &amp; Kerambrun 
<number box="[151,211,1702,1726]" pageId="4" pageNumber="382" value="1984.0">1984</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="383" pageId="4" pageNumber="382" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1269,2014]" lastBlockId="5.[151,1436,151,896]" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="383" pageId="4" pageNumber="382">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1737,1762]" pageId="4" pageNumber="382">Remarks.</emphasis>
The generic diagnosis provided by 
<bibRefCitation author="Delgado-Blas" box="[758,1165,1737,1762]" pageId="4" pageNumber="382" refString="Delgado-Blas, V. H. &amp; Diaz-Diaz, O. (2013) Malacoceros longiseta, a new species of Spionidae (Annelida: Polychaeta) from Venezuela. Marine Biodiversity, 43, 181 - 187. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1007 / s 12526 - 013 - 0144 - 9" type="journal article" year="2013">
Delgado-Blas &amp; Díaz-Díaz (
<number box="[1099,1158,1738,1762]" pageId="4" pageNumber="382" value="2013.0">2013</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
includes a number of characters which formerly had not been considered. Hence it can be regarded an appropriate attempt for the refinement of diagnosis. Many generic diagnoses are evidently not sufficient and the assignment of species is not reliable. This applies also to 
<taxonomicName box="[482,627,1845,1870]" class="Polychaeta" family="Spionidae" genus="Malacoceros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spionida" pageId="4" pageNumber="382" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[482,627,1845,1870]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="382">Malacoceros</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The latest example is the publication by 
<bibRefCitation author="Sikorski" box="[1108,1285,1845,1870]" pageId="4" pageNumber="382" refString="Sikorski, A. V. (2013) New combination for Malacoceros jirkovi and a key for Spio (Polychaeta: Annelida) from Norwegian waters and adjacent Arctic areas. Zoosystematica Rossica, 22, 172 - 180." type="journal article" year="2013">
Sikorski (
<number box="[1218,1277,1846,1870]" pageId="4" pageNumber="382" value="2013.0">2013</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
in which the author proposes the transfer of 
<taxonomicName authority="Sikorski, 1992" authorityName="Sikorski" authorityYear="1992" box="[499,894,1881,1906]" class="Polychaeta" family="Spionidae" genus="Malacoceros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spionida" pageId="4" pageNumber="382" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="jirkovi">
<emphasis box="[499,724,1881,1906]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="382">Malacoceros jirkovi</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Sikorski" box="[731,894,1881,1906]" pageId="4" pageNumber="382" refString="Sikorski, A. V. (1992) A new species of Malacoceros (Polychaeta: Spionidae) from the Norwegian Sea. Explorations of the Fauna of the Seas, 43, 105 - 108." type="journal article" year="1992">
Sikorski, 
<number box="[838,894,1882,1906]" pageId="4" pageNumber="382" value="1992.0">1992</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
to 
<taxonomicName authority="Fabricius, 1785" authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1785" box="[930,1160,1881,1906]" class="Polychaeta" family="Spionidae" genus="Spio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spionida" pageId="4" pageNumber="382" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[930,980,1882,1905]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="382">Spio</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Fabricius" box="[986,1160,1881,1906]" pageId="4" pageNumber="382" refString="Fabricius, O. (1785) Von dem Spio - Geschlecht einem neuen Wurmgeschlecht. Nereis seticornis und Nereis filicornis, mit Abbildungen. Schriften der Berlinischen Gesellschaft naturforschender Freunde, 6, 256 - 270." type="journal article" year="1785">
Fabricius, 
<number box="[1104,1160,1881,1906]" pageId="4" pageNumber="382" value="1785.0">1785</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. In the same publication the author considers that the morphologically similar 
<taxonomicName box="[756,876,1917,1942]" class="Polychaeta" family="Spionidae" genus="Malacoceros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spionida" pageId="4" pageNumber="382" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="indicus">
<emphasis box="[756,876,1917,1942]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="382">M. indicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
might also belong to 
<taxonomicName box="[1123,1173,1918,1941]" class="Polychaeta" family="Spionidae" genus="Spio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spionida" pageId="4" pageNumber="382" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1123,1173,1918,1941]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="382">Spio</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName authority="Sikorski, 1992" authorityName="Sikorski" authorityYear="1992" class="Polychaeta" family="Spionidae" genus="Spio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spionida" pageId="4" pageNumber="382" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="jirkovi" status="comb. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1188,1318,1917,1942]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="382">Spio jirkovi</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Sikorski" pageId="4" pageNumber="382" refString="Sikorski, A. V. (1992) A new species of Malacoceros (Polychaeta: Spionidae) from the Norwegian Sea. Explorations of the Fauna of the Seas, 43, 105 - 108." type="journal article" year="1992">
Sikorski, 
<number box="[151,208,1954,1978]" pageId="4" pageNumber="382" value="1992.0">1992</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[224,349,1953,1978]" pageId="4" pageNumber="382">comb. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is established based on 
<number box="[622,634,1954,1978]" pageId="4" pageNumber="382" value="1.0">1</number>
) the fixed number of four anal cirri opposed to a size-variable number of anal cirri in 
<taxonomicName box="[329,474,1989,2014]" class="Polychaeta" family="Spionidae" genus="Malacoceros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spionida" pageId="4" pageNumber="382" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[329,474,1989,2014]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="382">Malacoceros</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<number box="[492,507,1990,2014]" pageId="4" pageNumber="382" value="2.0">2</number>
) the absence of anterolateral horns and 
<number box="[974,988,1990,2014]" pageId="4" pageNumber="382" value="3.0">3</number>
) the arrangement of teeth in a tandem pattern instead of a pair-wise arrangement. These arguments seem disputable. A fixed number of four anal cirri is not exclusive for 
<taxonomicName box="[364,414,189,212]" class="Polychaeta" family="Spionidae" genus="Spio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spionida" pageId="5" pageNumber="383" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[364,414,189,212]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="383">Spio</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but quite widespread among 
<taxonomicName box="[774,890,188,213]" class="Polychaeta" family="Spionidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spionida" pageId="5" pageNumber="383" phylum="Annelida" rank="family">Spionidae</taxonomicName>
. None of the published generic diagnoses for 
<taxonomicName box="[151,296,223,248]" class="Polychaeta" family="Spionidae" genus="Malacoceros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spionida" pageId="5" pageNumber="383" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,296,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="383">Malacoceros</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
state a size-variable number of anal cirri to be diagnostic. The term anterolateral horns might refer to morphologically similar but non-homologous structures within 
<taxonomicName box="[958,1070,260,285]" class="Polychaeta" family="Spionidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spionida" pageId="5" pageNumber="383" phylum="Annelida" rank="family">Spionidae</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[1102,1247,260,285]" class="Polychaeta" family="Spionidae" genus="Rhynchospio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spionida" pageId="5" pageNumber="383" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1102,1247,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="383">Rhynchospio</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[1276,1428,260,285]" class="Polychaeta" family="Spionidae" genus="Glandulospio" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spionida" pageId="5" pageNumber="383" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1276,1428,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="383">Glandulospio</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[151,317,295,320]" class="Polychaeta" family="Spionidae" genus="Scolecolepides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spionida" pageId="5" pageNumber="383" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,317,295,320]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="383">Scolecolepides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[334,491,295,320]" class="Polychaeta" family="Spionidae" genus="Glyphochaeta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spionida" pageId="5" pageNumber="383" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[334,491,295,320]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="383">Glyphochaeta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[508,656,297,320]" class="Polychaeta" family="Spionidae" genus="Pygospiopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spionida" pageId="5" pageNumber="383" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[508,656,297,320]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="383">Pygospiopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[672,784,295,320]" class="Polychaeta" family="Spionidae" genus="Lindaspio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spionida" pageId="5" pageNumber="383" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[672,784,295,320]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="383">Lindaspio</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[801,923,295,320]" class="Polychaeta" family="Spionidae" genus="Atherospio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spionida" pageId="5" pageNumber="383" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[801,923,295,320]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="383">Atherospio</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[940,1069,295,320]" class="Polychaeta" family="Spionidae" genus="Spiophanes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spionida" pageId="5" pageNumber="383" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[940,1069,295,320]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="383">Spiophanes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[1085,1199,297,320]" class="Polychaeta" family="Spionidae" genus="Microspio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spionida" pageId="5" pageNumber="383" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1085,1199,297,320]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="383">Microspio</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, etc.) and a detailed review of this character is certainly required for all taxa (Meißner 
<emphasis box="[890,946,332,357]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="383">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[952,1013,332,356]" pageId="5" pageNumber="383" value="2014.0">2014</number>
). However, the prostomial shape of 
<taxonomicName class="Polychaeta" family="Spionidae" genus="Spio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spionida" pageId="5" pageNumber="383" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="jirkovi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="383">S. jirkovi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
being subtriangular, seems rather unusual for 
<taxonomicName box="[758,808,368,391]" class="Polychaeta" family="Spionidae" genus="Spio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spionida" pageId="5" pageNumber="383" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[758,808,368,391]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="383">Spio</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The absence of paired teeth is not uncommon among 
<taxonomicName box="[151,296,404,429]" class="Polychaeta" family="Spionidae" genus="Malacoceros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spionida" pageId="5" pageNumber="383" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,296,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="383">Malacoceros</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species (e.g., 
<taxonomicName authority="Graff, Blake &amp; Wishner, 2008" authorityName="Graff, Blake &amp; Wishner" authorityYear="2008" box="[471,983,404,429]" class="Polychaeta" family="Spionidae" genus="Malacoceros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spionida" pageId="5" pageNumber="383" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="jennicus">
<emphasis box="[471,607,405,428]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="383">M. jennicus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Graff" box="[620,983,404,429]" pageId="5" pageNumber="383" refString="Graff, J. R., Blake, J. A. &amp; Wishner, K. F. (2008) A new species of Malacoceros (Polychaeta: Spionidae) from Kick'em Jenny, a hydrothermally active submarine volcano in the Lesser Antilles Arc. Journal of the Marine Biological Association of the United Kingdom, 88, 925 - 930. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1017 / s 0025315408001884" type="journal article" year="2008">
Graff, Blake &amp; Wishner, 
<number box="[924,983,404,428]" pageId="5" pageNumber="383" value="2008.0">2008</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Claparede, 1870" authorityName="Claparede" authorityYear="1870" box="[1000,1388,404,429]" class="Polychaeta" family="Spionidae" genus="Malacoceros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spionida" pageId="5" pageNumber="383" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="fuliginosus">
<emphasis box="[1000,1166,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="383">M. fuliginosus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Claparede" box="[1186,1381,404,429]" pageId="5" pageNumber="383" refString="Claparede, E. (1870) Les Annelides Chetopodes du Golfe de Naples. Troisieme partie. Memoires de la Societe de Physique et d'Histoire Naturelle de Geneve, 20 (2), 365 - 542." type="journal article" year="1870">
Claparède, 
<number box="[1321,1381,404,428]" pageId="5" pageNumber="383" value="1870.0">1870</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Schmarda, 1861" authorityName="Schmarda" authorityYear="1861" class="Polychaeta" family="Spionidae" genus="Colobranchus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spionida" pageId="5" pageNumber="383" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="tetracerus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="383">M. tetracerus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Schmarda" box="[281,469,439,464]" pageId="5" pageNumber="383" refString="Schmarda, L. K. (1861) Neue wirbellose Thiere beobachtet und gesammelt auf einer Reise um die Erde 1853 bis 1857. Vol. 1. Turbellarien, Rotatorien und Anneliden. Wilhelm Engelmann, Leipzig, xviii + 66, 15 fine hand-coloured plates." type="journal article" year="1861">
Schmarda, 
<number box="[410,469,439,464]" pageId="5" pageNumber="383" value="1861.0">1861</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Delgado-Blas &amp; Diaz-Diaz, 2010" authorityName="Delgado-Blas &amp; Diaz-Diaz" authorityYear="2010" box="[491,1066,439,464]" class="Polychaeta" family="Spionidae" genus="Malacoceros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spionida" pageId="5" pageNumber="383" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="cariacoensis">
<emphasis box="[491,671,441,464]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="383">M. cariacoensis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Delgado-Blas" box="[681,1066,439,464]" pageId="5" pageNumber="383" refString="Delgado-Blas, V. H. &amp; Diaz-Diaz, O. (2010) Description of two new species of Malacoceros and Rhynchospio spionids (Polychaeta: Spionidae) from the Grand Caribbean region. Revista Chilena de Historia Natural, 83, 249 - 257. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.4067 / s 0716 - 078 x 2010000200006" type="journal article" year="2010">
Delgado-Blas &amp; Díaz-Díaz, 
<number box="[1005,1066,440,464]" pageId="5" pageNumber="383" value="2010.0">2010</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
). On the other hand, 
<taxonomicName box="[1309,1429,439,464]" class="Polychaeta" family="Spionidae" genus="Malacoceros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spionida" pageId="5" pageNumber="383" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="indicus">
<emphasis box="[1309,1429,439,464]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="383">M. indicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the species 
<bibRefCitation author="Sikorski" box="[286,464,476,501]" pageId="5" pageNumber="383" refString="Sikorski, A. V. (2013) New combination for Malacoceros jirkovi and a key for Spio (Polychaeta: Annelida) from Norwegian waters and adjacent Arctic areas. Zoosystematica Rossica, 22, 172 - 180." type="journal article" year="2013">
Sikorski (
<number box="[397,456,476,500]" pageId="5" pageNumber="383" value="2013.0">2013</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
considers closely related to 
<taxonomicName box="[797,901,476,501]" class="Polychaeta" family="Spionidae" genus="Spio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spionida" pageId="5" pageNumber="383" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="jirkovi">
<emphasis box="[797,901,476,501]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="383">S. jirkovi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, has paired apical teeth and hence contradicts Sikorski´s line of argument.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1436,151,896]" pageId="5" pageNumber="383">
There are also good reasons why 
<taxonomicName box="[590,694,548,573]" class="Polychaeta" family="Spionidae" genus="Spio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spionida" pageId="5" pageNumber="383" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="jirkovi">
<emphasis box="[590,694,548,573]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="383">S. jirkovi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is not in agreement with the generic diagnosis of 
<taxonomicName box="[1280,1329,549,572]" class="Polychaeta" family="Spionidae" genus="Spio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spionida" pageId="5" pageNumber="383" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1280,1329,549,572]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="383">Spio</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. For this species nuchal organs being small elongate grooves lateral to the posterior tip of the prostomium have been observed (Meißner 
<emphasis box="[374,432,620,645]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="383">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[442,503,620,644]" pageId="5" pageNumber="383" value="2014.0">2014</number>
). Metameric dorsal ciliated organs are not discernable (Meißner 
<emphasis box="[1244,1301,620,645]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="383">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[1311,1372,620,644]" pageId="5" pageNumber="383" value="2014.0">2014</number>
). The same applies to 
<taxonomicName box="[335,455,655,680]" class="Polychaeta" family="Spionidae" genus="Malacoceros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spionida" pageId="5" pageNumber="383" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="indicus">
<emphasis box="[335,455,655,680]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="383">M. indicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(this paper and cited literature herein). For 
<taxonomicName box="[957,1007,656,679]" class="Polychaeta" family="Spionidae" genus="Spio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spionida" pageId="5" pageNumber="383" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[957,1007,656,679]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="383">Spio</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
nuchal organs with short median and long lateral ciliary bands, extending to chaetiger 
<number box="[696,710,692,716]" pageId="5" pageNumber="383" value="2.0">2</number>
or 
<number box="[746,761,692,716]" pageId="5" pageNumber="383" value="3.0">3</number>
, are typical and metameric dorsal ciliated organs are usually present and easily detected under the light microscope after methyl green staining. Ventral epidermal glands are usually present in anterior and middle chaetigers of 
<taxonomicName box="[743,793,765,788]" class="Polychaeta" family="Spionidae" genus="Spio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spionida" pageId="5" pageNumber="383" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[743,793,765,788]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="383">Spio</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species. Such glands could not be detected in 
<taxonomicName box="[1324,1436,764,789]" class="Polychaeta" family="Spionidae" genus="Spio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spionida" pageId="5" pageNumber="383" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="jirkovi">
<emphasis box="[1324,1436,764,789]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="383">M. jirkovi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
nor in 
<taxonomicName box="[228,348,799,824]" class="Polychaeta" family="Spionidae" genus="Malacoceros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spionida" pageId="5" pageNumber="383" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="indicus">
<emphasis box="[228,348,799,824]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="383">M. indicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Therefore we do not agree with the new combination proposed by 
<bibRefCitation author="Sikorski" box="[1129,1306,799,824]" pageId="5" pageNumber="383" refString="Sikorski, A. V. (2013) New combination for Malacoceros jirkovi and a key for Spio (Polychaeta: Annelida) from Norwegian waters and adjacent Arctic areas. Zoosystematica Rossica, 22, 172 - 180." type="journal article" year="2013">
Sikorski (
<number box="[1240,1299,800,824]" pageId="5" pageNumber="383" value="2013.0">2013</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
and regard 
<taxonomicName box="[151,381,836,861]" class="Polychaeta" family="Spionidae" genus="Malacoceros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spionida" pageId="5" pageNumber="383" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="jirkovi">
<emphasis box="[151,381,836,861]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="383">Malacoceros jirkovi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as the valid name for the species. Nethertheless we admit, that the generic diagnosis of 
<taxonomicName box="[151,296,871,896]" class="Polychaeta" family="Spionidae" genus="Malacoceros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spionida" pageId="5" pageNumber="383" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,296,871,896]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="383">Malacoceros</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(and of several other genera) might not be sufficient in its current version.
</paragraph>
